ngdom":"Bristol, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Lepe, Huelva, Andalucia, Spain":"Lepe, Huelva, Andalucía, Spanje","Bristol, Gloucestershire, , England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"1340–1391":"1340–1391","1345–Female":"1345–Deceased","1375–1405":"1375–1405","1376–Male":"1376–Deceased","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1345":"1345","ABT 1376":"about 1376","1310":"1310","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1391":"1391","1405":"1405","Bristol, England, United Kingdom":"Bristol, England, United Kingdom","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Lepe, Huelva, Andalucia, Spain":"Lepe, Huelva, Andalusia, Spain","Bristol, Gloucestershire, , England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Paynell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southeastern):","possibly from Middle English <i>panel</i>, <i>panel(l)e</i> ‘cloth, saddle-cloth, saddle’ or ‘pane (of glass)’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a maker of such items.","from the Middle English personal name <i>Paynel</i> (Old French <i>Payenel</i>, Latin <i>Paganellus</i>), a pet form of   Payne   (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Payne","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i> (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>), a fairly common personal name among Normans. It derived from a word that originally meant ‘villager, rustic’, later ‘heathen’, but it had doubtless lost these connotations in its use as a late medieval personal name. This name has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","History: Thomas Payne, who was a freeman of Plymouth Colony in 1639, was the founder of a large American family, which included Robert Treat Paine (1731–1814), one of the signers of the Declaration of Independence. See also   Paine  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Paynell was born in 1340, in Bristol, England, United Kingdom as the son of Paynell. He had at least 2 sons with Soneta. He died in 1391, in Lepe, Huelva, Andalusia, Spain, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1340–1391":"1340–1391","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1375–1405":"1375–1405","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1345":"1345","ABT 1376":"umbes 1376","1310":"1310","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1391":"1391","1405":"1405","Bristol, England, United Kingdom":"Bristol, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Lepe, Huelva, Andalucia, Spain":"Lepe, Huelva, Andalucía, Hispaania","Bristol, Gloucestershire, , England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1340–1391":"1340–1391","1345–Female":"1345–Kuollut","1375–1405":"1375–1405","1376–Male":"1376–Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1345":"1345","ABT 1376":"noin 1376","1310":"1310","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1391":"1391","1405":"1405","Bristol, England, United Kingdom":"Bristol, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Lepe, Huelva, Andalucia, Spain":"Lepe, Huelva, Andalu